        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>- Sensitivity requirement :

There is no way to estimate the expected  [CII]158 flux from the shell although a part of the observed Lyman alpha emission may be associated with the shell. Since, however, the mechanical luminosity  of a superwind from a massive galaxy like the PDLA host is ~10^(44) ergs/s  or more (e.g, Heckman et al. 1990), PDRs in the shocked shell are expected to emit the bright [CII158 emission because the metal enrichment is already driven by a large number of Type II supernovae; note that carbon is one of alpha elements supplied by Type II supernovae. We therefore set the expected [CII]158 flux to the same value as that of the PDLA host (46 mJy).

- Calibration:

We do not need any special calibration, including bandpass accuracy.

- Scheduling/time constraints:

We have no constraints.

- Data rate:

According to OT, the data rate is 2.7 MB/s for the 12 m array and 1.1 MB/s for the ACA imaging.
These data rates are comfortably below the limit.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The required velocity resolution is 100 km/s because the expected line width is ~ 2000 km/s.
This red set is used to observe [CII] emission of the superwind-driven shocked shell around the PDLA host galaxy, covering 458.165 GHz to 461.765 GHz centered at 459.965 GHz. Two spectral bands (1.875 GHz each) are centered at 459.1025 GHz and 460.8275 GHz. TO obtain firm spectroscopic information, these two bands are overlapped with an interval of 0.15 GHz. Two more bands are not used because of little atmospheric transmission.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The required angular resolution is 1.0 arcsec. The observed size of Lyman alpha nebula is 5 arcsec (38 kpc). However, such a superwind-driven shocked shell is expected to be more extended (e.g., ~ 100 kpc). Therefore, we would like to use ACA as well as the 12 m array to map the extended PDRs in [CII]157.74 emission line.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
