    <prp:abstract>In order to investigate the origin of damped Lyman alpha absorption systems
(DLAs) at high redshift based on the superwind-driven shocked shell model
(Taniguchi &amp; Shioya 2001), we propose to observe a proximate DLA (PDLA)
found in the line of sight to the quasar SDSS J124020.91+145535.6 at z = 3.1
studied by Hennawi et al. (2009).
An extended Lyman alpha nebula is associated with this PDLA and its size is
5 arcsec (= 38 kpc), being identified as a Lyman alpha blob (LAB).
Since one of plausible origins of LABs is a superwind-driven shocked shell 
(Taniguchi &amp; Shioya 2000), this PDLA provides an ideal laboratory
to prove thie shocked shell model for DLAs.
Here we propose to observe this PDLA in [CII]157.74 emission in the Band 8
on ALMA. Our main science goals are to detect [CII]157.74 emission from
the PDLA host and the shocked shell causing DLA features and investigate 
their dynamical properties in detail. This observation provides a bland-new
approach to understand the origin of high-redshift DLAs.

</prp:abstract>
